## 🌐 4.1 Introduction to Extensibility

### **Definition**

**Extensibility** in web technologies refers to the ability of a markup or design language to **adapt, expand, or evolve** over time — allowing developers to define new tags, structures, or features without breaking existing systems.

The web started as a collection of static HTML documents, but as applications grew complex, the need for more **flexible, structured, and semantically rich markup** emerged. This is where extensible systems like **SGML**, **XML**, **HTML5**, and **CSS3** come into play.

---

### **Why Extensibility Matters**

- The Internet changes constantly — new media types, devices, and standards appear every few years.
- Extensible formats allow backward compatibility — older browsers can ignore unknown tags without breaking pages.
- Extensible markup ensures **standardization** while still allowing **innovation**.

In short:

> Extensibility ensures that the web can evolve without collapsing.

---

## 🧩 4.2 SGML — Standard Generalized Markup Language

### **Definition**

**SGML (Standard Generalized Markup Language)** is a **meta-markup language** — meaning it is not used directly to mark up documents but to **define other markup languages** like HTML and XML.

It was developed in the 1980s (ISO 8879 standard, 1986) to describe document structure in a **platform-independent** way.

---

### **Purpose of SGML**

SGML was designed to:

- Separate *content* from *presentation*.
- Define *document structure rules* (e.g., what tags can appear inside what elements).
- Allow organizations to design their own document formats (called **Document Type Definitions – DTDs**).

---

### **How SGML Works**

SGML allows you to define:

1. **Element Types** — the tags used (like `<title>`, `<para>`).
1. **Attributes** — additional properties of those tags.
1. **Rules (DTD)** — define which elements are allowed within others.

---

### **Example: Simplified SGML Document**

```html
<!DOCTYPE ARTICLE SYSTEM "article.dtd">
<ARTICLE>
  <TITLE>History of the Internet</TITLE>
  <AUTHOR>David Jones</AUTHOR>
  <BODY>
    <P>The Internet was born from ARPANET...</P>
  </BODY>
</ARTICLE>
```

Here:

- The `<!DOCTYPE>` line references a **DTD** file defining the structure.
- `<ARTICLE>` is a user-defined element — SGML allows that flexibility.

---

### **Advantages of SGML**

- Highly structured and extensible.
- Standardized way to represent complex documents.
- Platform and device independent.
- Ideal for organizations like government, defense, and research institutions needing reusable documentation systems.

---

### **Disadvantages**

- Too **complex** for web use.
- Hard to implement in browsers.
- Parsing SGML is resource-heavy — not suitable for real-time web rendering.

Hence, the web community simplified SGML into a lighter, more usable form — **HTML**.

---

## 🌍 4.3 HTML — The Web’s Child of SGML

### **How HTML Originated from SGML**

In the early 1990s, **Tim Berners-Lee** created the **World Wide Web** using HTML, which was based on SGML principles but simplified for online use.

**HTML (HyperText Markup Language)** adopted SGML’s core idea — marking up content using tags — but removed complex DTDs and formal declarations.

---

### **HTML Evolution Timeline**

{% table %}
- Version
- Year
- Key Features
---
- HTML 1.0
- 1991
- Basic text, links, images
---
- HTML 2.0
- 1995
- Forms, basic structure
---
- HTML 3.2
- 1997
- Tables, scripting support
---
- HTML 4.01
- 1999
- CSS support, separation of style and content
---
- XHTML 1.0
- 2000
- XML-based strict syntax
---
- **HTML5**
- **2014 (W3C Recommendation)**
- Multimedia, semantics, APIs, offline storage
{% /table %}

---

## 🧠 4.4 HTML5 — The Modern Standard

HTML5 is the **fifth major version** of HTML, jointly developed by **W3C (World Wide Web Consortium)** and **WHATWG**.\
It is designed to be **extensible, semantic, and multimedia-ready**.

### **Goals of HTML5**

1. Provide **better structure** for modern web content.
1. Support **rich media (video, audio, graphics)** without plugins.
1. Enable **offline applications** and **local storage**.
1. Integrate **APIs** for device interaction (camera, location, drag-and-drop).
1. Improve **semantics** for accessibility and SEO.

---

### **New Structural Elements**

HTML5 introduced meaningful, semantic tags replacing generic `<div>` blocks:

{% table %}
- Element
- Purpose
---
- `<header>`
- Defines introductory content or navigation
---
- `<nav>`
- Defines navigation menus
---
- `<main>`
- Defines the central content
---
- `<article>`
- Represents independent, self-contained content
---
- `<section>`
- Groups related content
---
- `<aside>`
- Defines sidebars, ads, or complementary info
---
- `<footer>`
- Defines footer or copyright info
{% /table %}

**Example:**

```html
<header>
  <h1>News Portal</h1>
  <nav>
    <a href="#world">World</a> | <a href="#sports">Sports</a>
  </nav>
</header>

<article>
  <h2>Global Economy Updates</h2>
  <p>World markets showed mixed results...</p>
</article>
```

---

### **New Input Types for Forms**

HTML5 added new input types to make data entry easier and more accurate.

{% table %}
- Input Type
- Example
---
- `email`
- `<input type="email">`
---
- `url`
- `<input type="url">`
---
- `date`
- `<input type="date">`
---
- `number`
- `<input type="number" min="1" max="10">`
---
- `range`
- `<input type="range" min="0" max="100">`
---
- `color`
- `<input type="color">`
{% /table %}

---

### **Multimedia Tags**

HTML5 eliminated the need for plugins like Flash by introducing native multimedia support.

```html
<video controls>
  <source src="movie.mp4" type="video/mp4">
</video>

<audio controls>
  <source src="sound.mp3" type="audio/mpeg">
</audio>
```

---

### **Canvas and SVG Graphics**

HTML5 supports dynamic graphics rendering through:

- `<canvas>` element (for 2D drawing using JavaScript)
- `<svg>` (Scalable Vector Graphics for resolution-independent visuals)

**Example:**

```html
<canvas id="draw" width="200" height="200"></canvas>
```

JavaScript can then draw lines, shapes, and animations inside the canvas.

---

### **APIs Introduced by HTML5**

{% table %}
- API
- Purpose
---
- **Geolocation API**
- Retrieves user’s physical location.
---
- **Web Storage API**
- Stores data locally (`localStorage`, `sessionStorage`).
---
- **Web Workers**
- Runs scripts in the background for multitasking.
---
- **Offline Web Applications**
- Allows apps to run without internet.
---
- **Drag and Drop API**
- Enables interactive movement of elements.
{% /table %}

---

### **HTML5 Extensibility**

HTML5 is designed to be **extensible and backward-compatible**.\
This means:

- Unknown tags are ignored gracefully.

- Future browsers can introduce new tags without breaking old pages.

- Custom data attributes (`data-*`) can be defined by developers:

  ```html
  <div data-user="arslanakbar" data-role="editor"></div>
  ```

---

### **Advantages of HTML5**

- Native support for audio, video, and graphics.
- Cleaner, semantic markup.
- Better mobile compatibility and responsive design.
- Built-in APIs for real-time applications.
- Offline capability.

### **Disadvantages**

- Some APIs still not fully supported across all browsers.
- Requires modern browsers for advanced features.
- Older HTML versions or legacy systems may need adaptation.

---

## 🎨 4.5 CSS3 — The Design Revolution

### **Definition**

**CSS3** (Cascading Style Sheets, Level 3) is the modern standard for controlling **layout, colors, fonts, animations, and responsiveness** of web pages.

It extends earlier CSS versions by dividing the specification into **modules**, each handling a different feature set (Selectors, Backgrounds, Transforms, Animations, etc.).

---

### **Major CSS3 Features**

#### 1. **Selectors**

New selectors enable more precise targeting of elements.

```css
input:focus { border-color: blue; }
p:first-child { color: red; }
```

#### 2. **Rounded Corners and Shadows**

```css
div {
  border-radius: 10px;
  box-shadow: 2px 2px 10px gray;
}
```

#### 3. **Gradients and Backgrounds**

```css
background: linear-gradient(to right, red, orange, yellow);
```

#### 4. **Transitions and Animations**

Allows smooth effects without JavaScript.

```css
div {
  transition: background-color 0.5s;
}
div:hover {
  background-color: yellow;
}
```

#### 5. **2D/3D Transforms**

```css
transform: rotate(45deg);
```

#### 6. **Flexbox and Grid Layouts**

Provides modern, flexible layouts for different screen sizes.

```css
.container {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: space-between;
}
```

#### 7. **Media Queries**

Core feature for **Responsive Web Design**.

```css
@media (max-width: 768px) {
  body { font-size: 14px; }
}
```

---

### **CSS3 Modules**

CSS3 is modular — it has separate specifications like:

- **Selectors Module**
- **Box Model Module**
- **Backgrounds & Borders**
- **Transitions & Animations**
- **Text Effects**
- **Media Queries**
- **Flexible Box Layout**
- **Grid Layout**

This modular design makes CSS **extensible** — new modules can be added without rewriting the entire standard.

---

### **Advantages of CSS3**

- Enables mobile-first responsive design.
- Eliminates dependency on JavaScript for animations.
- Reduces page load time (smaller CSS vs. images).
- Greater aesthetic control (fonts, shadows, gradients).
- Backward-compatible with older CSS2 syntax.

---

### **Example: Complete HTML5 + CSS3 Web Page**

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <title>My Modern Page</title>
  <style>
    body {
      font-family: 'Arial', sans-serif;
      background: linear-gradient(to bottom, #f0f8ff, #ffffff);
      margin: 0; padding: 0;
    }
    header {
      background: #0066cc;
      color: white;
      text-align: center;
      padding: 20px;
    }
    section {
      display: flex;
      justify-content: space-around;
      padding: 20px;
    }
    article {
      width: 45%;
      background: white;
      border-radius: 10px;
      box-shadow: 2px 2px 10px rgba(0,0,0,0.1);
      padding: 15px;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <header>
    <h1>Welcome to Arslan’s Web</h1>
  </header>
  <section>
    <article>
      <h2>HTML5 Section</h2>
      <p>HTML5 brings structure and semantics to web pages.</p>
    </article>
    <article>
      <h2>CSS3 Section</h2>
      <p>CSS3 enhances design with flexible layouts and animations.</p>
    </article>
  </section>
</body>
</html>
```

---

## 🧠 4.6 Summary

- **SGML** introduced the concept of extensible markup — defining document rules through DTDs.
- **HTML5** evolved from SGML, focusing on semantics, multimedia, and modern APIs.
- **CSS3** added powerful layout, animation, and design capabilities.
- All three together represent **extensibility in action** — the ability of web technologies to grow and adapt while maintaining backward compatibility.

In short:

> SGML gave birth to the web’s structure.\
HTML5 defined its modern semantics and behavior.\
CSS3 made it beautiful, responsive, and alive.
